As thus; the evidence of the matter appears as tranparent as Chrytal, and he who has but half an eye in his head, cannot chue but be made enible of it, at the very firt bluh; All we who live near the City, mut unavoidably upon the declining condition of our bet Patients, evermore be Subject to have ome or other of them to be brought down upon us. The new Phyitian is like the rieing Sun; every ones eye is cat upon him for ome Ray of comfort: his preence always brings hope along with it, at leat, though it hould afford nothing more, And what ever falls from his mouth, hit or mis,


is uually eteemed of by the company as little les then Oracle. The women never fail to gather about uch a one at his firt arrival; whoe hearts as they are ever tender, o are their tongues talkative: And I pray, Good Sir cry they, what may your Judgment be in this matter, life or death? we have had a retles night here: uch and uch things have been adminitred before your coming: we wih they may not have been too hot nor too cold: Do you believe them to have been all proper? Ah! this is lucious language to a proud heart and a haughty mind! this feeds the welling humor till it be ready to burt again, and this flyblows the mans head with conceitednes, o as to make him utterly forgetful of his duty both to himelf and others: For whilt the bladder of pride is thus bloated up, he takes himelf for ome other Creature then what really he is, and looks upon all his equals with pity and didain. And now he is put into the way his Genius o much inclines him to, he may very well be let alone to act his own part: For eeing others have been forward to declare the good liking they have of him, he is reolved not to be over-bahful in etting a value upon himelf; be domineers, and he dictates, and his entences are all irreverable, admitting of neither diquiition, alteration nor appeal;


but mut all be ubmitted to with a blind obedience, and an implicate faith: and nothing in fine can ever be performed regularly, and as it ought, unles happening to agree with the exact platform of this wie contrivance. There is no tutor inults more imperiouly over his young pupil, then ome that I could name, do over thoe they are uper-induced to conult withal: epecially if they find any of the family peeping in upon them to make obervation of their Actions: for then omething mut be poken in a key higher then ordinary: Some latent Error upon a more erious review dicovered, and the pen natched out of the others hand to mend it withal, and if it be but on purpoe to hew who gives check to the conultation, and where alone the Legilative Power lies.

There is a certain Stock of Radical Moiture to be oberved within the Body of every man, which defues it elf thoroughout each minute particle thereof, and without which 'tis impoible for any due Temperament long to be preerved; or for the Soul and Body to be held in a State of Conjunction one with another: This Moiture is uppoed to be perpetually ubject to decay, and that upon a double account; Firt as being prey • d upon by the Heat it is contempered withal; and Secondly, becaue the Subtantial Parts in which it is founded as an Accident in its Subject, are liable to be conum • d alo; but the Blood of Man is either the Immediate Matter, or at leat wie the Matter but once removed, out of which the Parts o decaying, are all to be framed a new, and the Heat and Moiture which we have proved to be the ineperable Concomitants of the Blood, are the ame for kind, though not for Purity, with the Innate and Radical, that are Seated in the everal
Parts of the Body. And 'tis only from the Addition of them, as we have been till uppoing, and in a manner enforced o very long to init upon the Proof of, becaue a Point o exceeding neceary to be thorowly undertood that the Primogenial are upheld. And therefore when ever it o falls out, that any top hall be put to the Continuation of the Act of Nutrition (as tis very improbable but that there hould be ome, when ere the Blood out of which this Aid is only to be afforded, comes, though but in Part, to be Subtracted and taken away) thoe Parts of the Body, which both might and ought to have been recruted thereby, will mot certainly be deprived for ome time, at leatwie, of uch a Proportion of Heat and Moiture as had been realy communicated unto them, had this hinderance never been; becaue, as goes the Subtance, o in like manner goes the Accident; they live and die, rie and fall together: and when ever the one is withheld the other of Coure will unavoidably be kept back alo; and though it hould happly be but for a time, that very Conceion alone is ufficient for our purpoe; becaue, according to the Intances alledged, the two Original Qualities before mentioned, mut, for lack of uch wonted Acceions, be left under a neceity of o much the greater wating and decay;
and as a conequent of that their final Extirpation, be o much the nearer its Accomplihment.
